Characters that might appear in the generated variable name as any but the first character.
Characters that might appear in the generated variable name as first character.

Creates an application-level lock on a session. The disadvantage is that the lock is not enforced by the database and thus other, unaware parts of the application could still concurrently modify the session. The advantage is it does not require a transaction.
Generates a relative path based on the current request path, e.g. ".
Indicates that an invalid argument was passed.

Issues a real row lock. Since it uses a transaction between opening and closing a session, you have to be careful when you use same database connection that you also use for your application logic. This mode is the default because it's the only reliable solution across DBMSs.
Magic used for validating the format of a MO file as well as detecting if the machine used to create that file was big endian.
Magic used for validating the format of a MO file as well as detecting if the machine used to create that file was little endian.
Marks a constraint that can be put onto classes.
Marks a constraint that can be put onto properties.
Marks an instance with a value that is extremely likely to be correct.
Marks an instance with a value that is likely to be correct.
Marks an instance with a value that is very likely to be correct.
Marks an instance with a value that may be correct.

No locking is done. This means sessions are prone to loss of data due to race conditions of concurrent requests to the same session. The last session write will win in this case. It might be useful when you implement your own logic to deal with this like an optimistic approach.
Regex fragment that matches an escaped character in a double quoted string.
Rounds to the nearest number and halves away from zero.
Rounds to the nearest number and halves to the next even number.
Rounds to the nearest number and halves towards zero.
Specifies that a node should be cascaded.
Specifies that a node should not be cascaded.
Specifies that a node's value should always be iterated. If the value is not an instance of {@link \Traversable}, an exception should be thrown.
Specifies that a node's value should be iterated only if it is an instance of {@link \Traversable}.
Specifies that a node's value should never be iterated.
The AUTHENTICATION_FAILURE event occurs after a user cannot be authenticated by any of the providers.
The AUTHENTICATION_SUCCESS event occurs after a user is authenticated by one provider.
The COMMAND event allows you to attach listeners before any command is executed by the console. It also allows you to modify the command, input and output before they are handled to the command.
The CONTROLLER event occurs once a controller was found for handling a request.
The CONTROLLER_ARGUMENTS event occurs once controller arguments have been resolved.
The ERROR event occurs when an uncaught exception or error appears.
The EXCEPTION event occurs when an uncaught exception appears.
The FINISH_REQUEST event occurs when a response was generated for a request.
The FormEvents::POST_SET_DATA event is dispatched at the end of the Form::setData() method.
The FormEvents::POST_SUBMIT event is dispatched after the Form::submit() once the model and view data have been denormalized.
The FormEvents::PRE_SET_DATA event is dispatched at the beginning of the Form::setData() method.
The HTML5 datetime-local format as defined in http://w3c.github.io/html-reference/datatypes.html#form.data.datetime-local.

The INTERACTIVE_LOGIN event occurs after a user has actively logged into your website. It is important to distinguish this action from non-interactive authentication methods, such as: - authentication based on your session.
The PRE_SUBMIT event is dispatched at the beginning of the Form::submit() method.
The REQUEST event occurs at the very beginning of request dispatching.
The RESPONSE event occurs once a response was created for replying to a request.
The SUBMIT event is dispatched just before the Form::submit() method transforms back the normalized data to the model and view data.
The SWITCH_USER event occurs before switch to another user and before exit from an already switched user.
The TERMINATE event allows you to attach listeners after a command is executed by the console.
The TERMINATE event occurs once a response was sent.
The VIEW event occurs when the return value of a controller is not a Response instance.
The directory name of the currency data.
The directory name of the language data.
The directory name of the locale data.
The directory name of the region data.
The directory name of the script data.
The maximum supported length of a PCRE subpattern name http://pcre.org/current/doc/html/pcre2pattern.html#SEC16.
The name of the group given to all constraints with no explicit group.
The namespace to load constraints from by default.
The namespace used to store values in the session.
The number of resource bundles to buffer. Loading the same resource bundle for n locales takes up n spots in the buffer.
The prefix used for indenting nested error messages.
The return code for skipped commands, this will also be passed into the terminate event.
The size of the header of a MO file in bytes.
The variable in {@link FormView} used as cache key.
This attribute name can be used by the implementation if it needs to set a cookie on the Request when there is no actual Response, yet.

This string defines the characters that are automatically considered separators in front of optional placeholders (with default and no static text following). Such a single separator can be left out together with the optional placeholder from matching and generating URLs.
Use this constant for not provided username.
Whether to cast objects with a "__toString()" method to strings.
Whether to format {@link \DateTime} objects as RFC-3339 dates ("Y-m-d H:i:s").
